A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some accessible medicines already.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the patient's life may be significantly prolonged through a combination of medications that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines will no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarbons have effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently from all the medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the resistance problem.
In their work scientists find new, 'best' compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalcarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
