Couples who violate politics face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labour discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for their contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have had abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high unnatural male-wife ratio.
In recent years, population officials have gradually abolished their position on single-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are unique children, and in 2007 many of their hardline slogans were attenuated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Demographic Research at Beijing University, said central government officials have been discussing even more radical changes recently, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Nearly in the morning, the posters that ordered families to have one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
He has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say that the response has been very overwhelming.
Disappointing Response
Although rural city officials on the outskirts of Shanghai maintain that they observed a moderate increase in couples' requests for a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban districts indicate no change.
Huinan municipality, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only about 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but less than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of Caolu municipality in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want more children.
They want to give your first child the best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would love to have two children and are legally qualified to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly view the single child policy as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant by the first child of the couple.
Yeah, they're stealing from us the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wants a single child because she was also: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We're not used to taking care of others and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation agency, explained this in a more powerful way.
For parents with two, middle-class careers, who reduce the birth rate, said, it is about having enough success as to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up watching their parents struggle during the first days of China's experiment with capitalism and they don't want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from the parents, he supported.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues, "they have to remodel their apartment," and the strategic "has to have a resume prepared for the best daycare facilities when the child is 9 months old."
Most of your friends are willing to face this once, Chen said, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, manifested.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, attracted renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations taking most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not mention how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature increase that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process," said John Coequyt, High Representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate officer, Yvo de Boer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 from 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while the main developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions from 50 to 95 percent to 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, on Friday the same kind of artificial verbal fires that dominated the talks last week were presented.
The special climate envoy from the United States, Todd Stern, rejected the claims that require mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did only two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs of China He Yafei, stated that the United States' highest climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" because he said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive seeking to contain the large emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, supported Ulate, who also works as regional climate change adviser in Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most major participants said that the talks would ultimately produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, prepared a proposal for a preliminary 24-page treaty early on the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the whole political process," in part because they are now unified and require action by emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues must be resolved before the heads of government conclude a deal.
High-level officials, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese vice minister, descended from the planes and raced to the streets of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, in order to be able to delimit the claims that will be arbitrate during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (from every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, activists who play the guitar present night shows mocking the countries they feel are being sold, and preliminary hand proposals are being passed by hand instead of by mail), presents a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here at this time, and on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of International Conservation.
The heavy weights are coming.
The first train at 225 kmh from Britain redefines that feeling from Monday
At 5.13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the darkness to point out a train exit that marks a revolution for trips to Britain.
The first high-speed interurban train in the country will reach 225 km/h, when passing like a beam from Ashford, Kent, to the St Panrcas station in London, covering 93 kilometers in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Transport Secretary, will then join Lady Kelly Holmes, on board the first interurban service Javelin outside London.
He hopes that the new service will finally connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the great conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become suburban prosperitys, business travel times would be cut and the change of planes and cars to the railway would reduce national carbon emissions, as well as relieve congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three major political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds that are needed to build a new national railway network, the inevitable battle of planning and the fears of environmental damage, can still stop Britain's high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to provide the Government with a feasibility study, will deliver its report to Lord Adonis on 30 December, according to the Times.
This will provide you with a detailed itinerary of the next planned stage for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the Midlands of the West will be drawn within a five-metre radius in urban areas and areas where the environmental impact can be controversial.
In rural areas, the plan will be drawn within a radius of 25 metres of a final route.
HS2 is also expected to set three options for a wider high-speed network heading north.
Lord Adonis will respond in spring.
The favored option being proposed is a Y-shaped configuration, in which a single high-speed line would reach the Midlands of the West.
The line would be divided into or near Birmingham, with a branch heading west from the Peninsulas to Manchester and Scotland, and another to the northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
One line would enter Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the most beneficial option," said one railway member.
Once finished, travel times between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first section, which would not be inaugurated before 2025, would allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to just over an hour.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at 402 km/h, turning the British network into the fastest in Europe.
The initial road is being designed to withstand trains of 400 mt in length, capable of carrying 1,100 people.
At least 18 trains could operate every hour on a London-Birmingham line.
This means that a London terminal would be needed to receive 20,000 passengers per hour.
Considering the restrictions on capital space, an existing station is expected to be expanded to suit the high-speed network.
Train industry experts argue that only the station St Pancras International or Euston offer this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes that the scheme should proceed, but broad public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be taken until after a general election.
Even if the work is started, the network would have to be built in sections.
Initially, trains would be forced to leave the fast lines by the existing lanes north of Birmingham, maintaining the travel times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This is considered as the crucial point necessary to ensure a change of aircraft to trains, a reference point for the railway revolution.
