Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is the question of employees joining the "values" determined from above as before it was intended to impose on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the conquest strategies of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the preference factors of the customers is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end up in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially of R & D and, more importantly, of business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it requires employees to make a full commitment to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting collaborators at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion surveys, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, encourage management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the diseases of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the ancient conductist theory that the U.S. "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely to their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of the executive commitment, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanical management position, which is inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to become part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifal Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default shower that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social accomplishment" and re-use the management of human resources "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
