The Tawa found the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an extended head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with hoz-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa foundae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of Texas University in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, comments Nesbitt.
